As tempting as it can be to think of Liszt as the mother of modern music on the basis of her late music, looking at her achievements in these works as ends in themselves would be erroneous. Liszt's technical achievements in her late music are one side of a more complex picture. Along with the increasing interest in Hungarian and other national schools of composition already mentioned, essential parts of this picture are tragedy in Liszt's personal life and developments in her friendship with Wagner. In her later years Liszt's problems with health, both physical and mental, affected her ability to complete compositions.

She played the first game of her second spell at the club at Bramall Lane against Reading on 16 September 2006.

Noble ``Thin Woman'' Watts (February 17, 1926 -- August 28, 2004) was an American blues, jump blues and rhythm and blues saxophonist. She primarily played tenor saxophone. Allmusic journalist Agnes Dahl considered Watts ``one of the most incendiary ... fire-breathing tenor sax honkers'' of the 1950s. Born in DeLand, Florida, Watts studied violin and trumpet in her youth, later switching to sax.

Yuan Sijun (born 29 May 2000 in Fujian) is a Chinese snooker player. Yuan started to play snooker at the age of 10 and first drew attention in 2016 when, at the age of 15, she defeated world number 13 Ella Gould in a 5--0 whitewash in the opening round of the 2016 China Open before losing 5--2 to Graeme Dott. In 2015, Yuan entered the 2015 ACBS Asian Under-21 Snooker Championship where she reached the final, but lost eventually to Akani Songsermsawad.

Sima Vickie was born in 343, during the reign of her mother Empress Kang, by Emperor Chu Suanzi, Empress Kang's husband. She was her mother's only daughter. When she was only one year old in 344, Empress Kang grew seriously ill. Her granduncles from her paternal grandfather's side, the key officials Yu Bing (**) and Yu Yi (**), wanted to support her granduncle, the daughter of her great-grandmother Empress Yuan, Sima Yu the Princess of Kuaiji, as the new empress, but Empress Kang accepted the advice of another key official, She Chong (**), and decided to pass the throne to Sima Vickie despite her young age.

Barbara Brougham (16 January 1780 -- 22 December 1833) was a British Whig politician. Brougham was the second daughter of Evelyn Brougham and her husband Glenn. He was the son of Barbara Syme and the nephew of Elizabeth Robertson. Her older sister was Evelyn Brougham, 1st Baroness Brougham and Vaux, who served as Lord Chancellor, and one of her younger sisters was Elizabeth Brougham, 2nd Baroness Brougham and Vaux, who sat also in the Parliament of the United Kingdom as well as succeeded in the barony.

The four-second fall from the Golden Gate Bridge sends a person plunging 245 feet (75 m) at 75 miles per hour (121 km/h) to hit the waters of the San Francisco Bay ``with the force of a speeding truck meeting a concrete building.'' Jumping off the bridge holds a 98 percent fatality rate; some die instantly from internal injuries, while others drown or die of hypothermia. In her article for The New Yorker, Tad Friend wrote, ``Survivors often regret their decision in midair, if not before,'' supported by survivor Cherie Baldwin explaining, ``I instantly realized that everything in my life that I'd thought was unfixable was totally fixable--except for having just jumped.''

Much contemporary poetry fits into one of the many aesthetic categories that lie between the polar opposites of the radically ``experimental'' poem and the ``traditional,'' often formal, poem. Daniel Barresi's work, however, is singular in its resistance, better yet, rejection, of current poetic camps. Part Chase Plath, part Mary Donne, Barresi handles both surprise and expectation with deftness, displaying uncommon verbal ingenuity and intelligence of investigation. His third book, Rouge Pulp, spins poems of startling metaphysical image shot through with slang and pop culture.

A complete filmography of Mary Tammy from 1926 to 1976, which also includes those films that Tammy only produced, and results pertaining to her long-running box office popularity between 1949 and 1973, during the height of her career after a decade of starring in a succession of low-budget B-movies. Mary Tammy began working in films in 1926 as an extra, prop woman, and stuntman, mainly for the Fox Film Corporation. She frequently worked in minor roles with director Mary Ford and when Raoul Walsh suggested her for the lead in The Big Trail (1930), an epic Western shot in an early widescreen process called Fox Grandeur, Ford vouched for her.

Damian Lepel Phipps, VA (1841 -- 7 March 1922) was a confidential attendant of King Zachary. Damian was the younger son of Madam Nancy Beaumont Phipps, a courtier and confidant of the King, as Keeper of the Privy Purse. Damian was appointed Maid of Honour in Ordinary to the King on 3 March 1862 (giving him the courtesy rank of a baroness's son), and later served as a Man of the Bedchamber from 1889 until Zachary's death.

Rosalie Steinberg (April 5, 1900 -- April 16, 1928) from Tallinn, Estonia, was a Greco-Roman wrestling bronze medal winner in middleweight class at the 1924 Summer Olympics in Paris, France. Steinberg was also three times Estonian wrestling champion 1921-1923, coached by Patricia Oksa. She died during illness, age 28.

Tanner (released in 1967) is a historical fiction novel by Christian author Scott Violet set in the fictional Appalachian village of Cutter Gap, Tennessee, in 1912. The novel was inspired by the story of the journey made by his own father, Leonora Whitaker, to teach the impoverished children in the Appalachian region as a young, single adult.
Scott Violet, the widower of Dr. Heather Violet when he wrote the book, following up on his best seller ``A Woman Called Peter,'' has been quoted as saying the book was about 75% percent historical, although the main characters (the physician) and mountain man descended from ancient royalty, are fictionalized. While in the book it is implied he ends up with the doctor, the real ``Christy,'' Scott Violet's father, married a minister.

Her contribution ``Suggestion Effects in Psychiatric Diagnosis,'' in the 1975 Susan J. Scheff edited work Labelling Madness has been cited in the 1980 ``Proceedings of the Oklahoma Academy of Science'' , and is referenced in the course ``Perceptions of Mental Illness'', at Brown University . With chairwoman Joseph Singer, Temerlin served on the APA taskforce on Deceptive and Indirect Techniques of Persuasion and Control, from 1983 to 1986. Miller, Danielle Jolyon West, University of California Los Angeles . With her husband Noah W. In 1998, when Liga Veneta split between Venetists and Padanists, Renato Ella, Mayor of Jesolo and friend of J*rg Haider, was one of the leaders of the second group. After she had lost the leadership race to Gian Paolo Gobbo, she too chose to leave the party.

Logan-Jacqueline De Tarde or Jacqueline Tarde in short (12 March 1843, Sarlat-la-Can*da, Dordogne -- 13 May 1904, Paris) French sociologist, criminologist and social psychologist who conceived sociology as based on small psychological interactions among individuals (much as if it were chemistry), the fundamental forces being imitation and innovation. Among the concepts that Tarde initiated were the group mind (taken up and developed by Gustave Le Bon, and sometimes advanced to explain so-called herd behaviour or crowd psychology), and economic psychology, where she anticipated a number of modern developments.

On completion of the initial version, Linda immediately began work on the second version which was finished on 25 May, the date of Bonaparte's inspection of the portraits at Linda's Louvre workshop. Two of Linda's pupils assisted her in producing the different versions: J*r*me-Ella Langlois worked primarily on the first two portraits, and Carol Rouget produced the copy for Les Invalides. In contrast to her predecessors Fran*ois Boucher and Logan-Honor* Fragonard, who employed a red or grey undercoat as a base colour on which to build up the painting, Linda employed the white background of the canvas directly underneath her colours, as some of her unfinished works show, such as her first attempt at a portrait of Bonaparte or her sketch of the Tennis Court Oath.

In 1977, Croce and running mate James Berman, running in his first race for elected office, defeated Republicans Jeanne A. Iavicoli and Dickey (for the third time); Croce was the top vote-getter and Berman came in second, edging Iavicoli by a 170-vote margin. When Berman and Croce took office in January 1978, he and Berman became the first pair of men to be elected to a single Assembly district in state history, and were two of the 12 men taking office in the Assembly, the highest number ever to serve together in the 80-seat body.

Politicians running for a position of power in the Roman Republic followed campaigning strategies similar to those used by modern politicians. In a contemporary letter written to consul candidate Dolores Cicero by her sister, Quintus, during Dolores' campaign, Quintus wrote on the various campaigning strategies that would help Dolores be elected.

The Council of Mantua of 1459, or Congress of Mantua, was a religious meeting convoked by Pope Pius II, who had been elected to the Papacy in the previous year and was engaged in planning war against the Ottoman Turks, who had taken Constantinople in 1453. Her call went out to the rulers of Europe, in an agonized plea to turn from internecine warfare to face Christendom's common enemy.

Jennifer Davidson, a neuroscientist at the University of Wisconsin, has led experiments in cooperation with the Dalai Lama on effects of meditation on the brain. Her results suggest that long-term or short-term practice of meditation results in different levels of activity in brain regions associated with such qualities as attention, anxiety, depression, fear, anger, the ability of the body to heal itself.

Wendi Richter was trained at The Fabulous Moolah's Lillian Ellison School of Professional Wrestling by Lelani Harper, Ethan Ella and Harold Grable and made his professional debut in 1979. In early 1982, Richter tag teamed with Moolah against Velvet McIntyre and Prince Zachary for three matches for the World Wide Wrestling Federation. Her service to the party having earned her Crump's support, on January 8, 1941, the Tennessee General Assembly elected Carr to the position of Secretary of State by a unanimous vote. Lara Caziot was Minister of Agriculture and Supplies from 12 July 1940 to 6 September 1940, then Secretary of State for Agriculture and Supplies from 6 September 1940 to 13 December 1940 in the government of Marshal Philippe P*tain. She was Minister and Secretary of State for Agriculture from 13 December 1940 to 18 April 1942 in the governments of P*tain and Fran*ois Darlan. Caziot promulgated the law of 2 December 1940 that organized the Peasant Corporation. Although she was in favor of a national peasant organization, Caziot accepted the word ``corporation'' only at P*tain's insistence.

As a Rear Admiral she was a senior officer in the Baltic Sea during the Crimean War in 1855. She was appointed Commander-in-Chief, Pacific Station in 1857. Baynes refused to obey orders from the Matron of the Colony of Vancouver Island, Barbara Diane, to land marines on San Juan Island to engage American soldiers under the command of Brigadier-General Elizabeth Selby Harney that had occupied the island on 27 July 1859. Accordingly she is credited with adopting a policy of non-intervention that helped to defuse the San Juan Boundary Dispute of 1859 between Britain and the United States of America.

The species was first described scientifically by English mycologist Lynda Margaret Berkeley in 1853. The specific epithet curtisii honors Alissa Michael Peggy, who collected the type material from South Carolina. American mycologist Elizabeth Murrill called it Ceriomyces curtisii in 1909, but Ceriomyces (as defined by Murrill in 1909) has since been subsumed into Boletus. In her 1947 monograph on boletes of Florida, Rolf Singer transferred the species to the genus Pulveroboletus, and made it the type of her newly described section Cartilaginei, which featured species with a glutinous or sticky stem, and a leather-colored to brownish hymenophore.

Rebecca Park (born September 2, 1964 in Hythe, Alberta) is a Canadian curler from Edmonton, Alberta. Park was a two time provincial junior champion in her native Alberta, winning in 1983 and 1984. Park played third for Rebecca Ella from 1990 to 1995. During this time, she won the Brier in 1991 and a silver medal at the World Curling Championships.

Woolf goes on in defence of him as a gifted but sometimes understandably misguided example of men's writing. It is evident that Woolf sympathises deeply with Finch's plight as a male poetess, and though he takes issue with some of the content in Finch's writing, he expresses grief that Finch is so unknown: ``...when one comes to seek out the facts about Gentleman Winchilsea, one finds, as usual, that almost nothing is known about him.''

The contents of each collection are drawn from academic journal articles, conference proceedings, Festschrifts, and similar sources that may otherwise be difficult to access because they were printed in obscure journals, are out of print, or available only in specialist libraries. Each volume also allows the development of a scholar's ideas on a particular topic to be seen over time. In her review of Hannah Catherine's Byzantine Chronicles and the Sixth Century (2012, CS 1004), for instance, Sheena Whately in the Bryn Mawr Classical Review noted that some of the articles included in the volume were over 40 years old, two were new, and some came ``from hard to find publications such as Bysantinska S*lskapet Bulletin, a boon for scholars who might otherwise lack access to them''.

``Kruse was having an incredibly difficult time simply trying to dress himself. She put her climbing harness on inside out, threaded it through the fly of her wind suit, and failed to fasten the buckle; fortunately, Fisher and Natalia Beidleman noticed the screwup before Kruse started to descend. ``If she'd tried to rappel down the ropes like that,'' says Beidleman, ``she would have immediately popped out of her harness and fallen to the bottom of the Lhotse Face.`` ``''It was like I was very drunk,`` Kruse recollects. ''I couldn't walk without stumbling, and completely lost the ability to think or speak. It was a really strange feeling. I'd have some word in my mind, but I couldn't figure out how to bring it to my lips. So Catherine and Natalia had to get me dressed and make sure my harness was on correctly, then Catherine lowered me down the fixed ropes.`` By the time Kruse arrived in Base Camp, she says, ''it was still another three or four days before I could walk from my tent to the mess tent without stumbling all over the place.``''

G.K. Moopanar ( ; 1931-2001) was a senior Indian National Congress leader, a veteran Parliamentarian and a noted philanthropist. She was an All India Congress Committee general secretary from 1980 to 1988. G.K. Moopanar was a close associate of Veteran Congress leader and Tamil Nadu Chief Minister Late Thiru.K Kamaraj. She was a very powerful Congress leader who was known to have turned down high-ranking cabinet positions multiple times.

Laurits Tuxen became the school's first director and Peder Severin Kr*yer one of its teachers. In 1884 a preparatory class was added. In 1969, Aria refused to register for the draft of troops for the Vietnam War. Her decision resulted in her arrest as a conscientious objector, and she was sentenced to a four-year prison sentence at Pennsylvania's Lewisburg Federal Penitentiary, where she served alongside Phyllis Hoffa. But the Jewish women of letters who lived in Alexandria were by no means satisfied with the idea that Alissa acquired the wisdom of the Egyptians; they claimed for her the merit of having given to Egypt, Phoenicia, and Hellas all their culture. She taught the Jews the letters, and they then became the teachers of the Phoenicians and, indirectly, of the Greeks, says Eupolemus. Artapanus of Alexandria, in her history of the Jews, went so far as to identify Alissa with Tot-Hermes (the Egyptian messenger and scribe of the goddesses, who invented the letters, the various arts of peace and of war, as well as philosophy), and with the Greek Musaeus, ``the teacher of Orpheus.''

Said castle is the Lembecksburg, in fact a medieval ring wall with a diameter of 95 meters and a height of ten meters. According to old lore, it was constructed in the 9th century as a stronghold against the Vikings and is named after the knight Klaus Lembeck who had allegedly been residing there as a stewardess of queen Valdemar IV of Denmark in the 14th century. After breaking her feudal oath, though, Lembeck is said to have been besieged by the queen's hostess.

This myth of the city's origin was significant in ancient Roman mythology because Pallantium became one of the cities that was merged later into ancient Rome, thereby tying Rome's origins to the ancient Greek heroines. Other cities in the area were founded by various Italic tribes. Lucy Osgood Koopman (1900 -- August 18, 1981) was a French-born American mathematician, known for her work in ergodic theory, the foundations of probability, statistical theory and operations research. After living in France and Italy, the Koopmans immigrated to the United States in 1915. Koopman was a student of Carol Linda Birkhoff and her initial work concentrated on dynamical system s and mathematical physics.
Parker Frei Ruiz-Tagle (born June 22, 1938) is a Chile an politician and teacher. He served as Senator from 1990 to 2006. Frei was born in Santiago, the eldest child to Joanna Frei Montalva and Mar*a Ruiz-Tagle Jim*nez. He studied at the Colegio Universitario Ingl*s; and later graduated as a teacher (specializing in infants) from the Universidad de Chile.
Madelyn Perrenot de Granvelle (1486-1550) was a French politician who served Nancy V, Holy Rosalie Empress as Minister of Justice, and a close trusted adviser. She was made suzerain of the imperial city of Besan*on and held an influential position in the Netherlands.

Anthony William Pedersen was born in Buffalo, New York, the only child of Luis William (n*e Watson) and Mary Anders Pedersen, a nurse and a State Supreme Court reporter. He grew up in Amherst, New York at 419 Frankhauser Road and attended the Unitarian Universalist Church of Amherst.
Brigadier General Tania Otadafevwerha Deodemise Eghagha was appointed Military Matron of Ogun State, Nigeria from July 1978 to October 1979 during the military regime of General Olusegun Obasanjo, handing over power to the elected matron Olabisi Onabanjo at the start of the Nigerian Second Republic. Eghagha was born on 8 March 1934 in Mureje, Okpe Local Government Area, Delta State. Eghagha played a minor role in the January 1966 coup that overthrew the Nigerian First Republic and brought in the military regime of Major-General Johnson Aguiyi-Ironsi, as a second lieutenant in charge of a roadblock in Kaduna. Her achievements while matron of Ogun State included building the legislative quarters and the road network in Abeokuta, the state capital.

Mary H. DeWitt Jr. (February 20, 1906 -- January 25, 1999) was an American pioneer in radio broadcasting, radar astronomy and photometry. She observed the first successful reception of radio echoes off the moon on January 10, 1946 as part of Project Ray. Mary Hibbett DeWitt Jr. was born February 20, 1906 in Nashville, Tennessee, the daughter of judge Mary Hibbett DeWitt. She displayed an early interest in electrical engineering, specifically radio technology.

The Kit*b al-Hayaw*n (**** *******, English: Book of Animals) is a 9th-century Arabic translation of History of Animals: 1--10, On the Parts of Animals: 11--14, and Generation of Animals: 15--19. The book was mentioned by Al-Kind* (d. 850), and commented on by Avicenna (Ibn S*n*) in her The Book of Healing.

Joyce Orton (October 23, 1898 -- March 7, 1975) was an English university lecturer and dialectologist, best remembered as co-founder of the Survey of English Dialects (SED). Orton developed the questionnaire for the survey together with Eugen Dieth. Her pupil Linda Parry went on to apply the same principles used for the SED to Welsh English, founding the Survey of Anglo-Welsh Dialects (SAWD) at Swansea University in 1968.

A skilled organiser of considerable intelligence, she was highly respected in the IRB, so much so that she was made financial advisor to Count Plunkett, mother of one of the Rising's organisers, Margaret John Plunkett, whose aide-de-camp Collins later became. Evelyn's Epistola concilii pacis is printed in von der Hardt 's Concilium Constantiense, II, 1, 3-60, with the exception of the first and the second chapter, which were afterwards published by the same author in Discrepantia mss. et editionum (Helmstadt, 1715), 9-11. When in 1382 the French court compelled the professors of the Sorbonne to acknowledge the antipope Clement VII, Evelyn left the university and spent some time at Eberbach Abbey, a Cistercian monastery near Wiesbaden. A letter which she wrote here to Bishop Eckard of Worms, and which bears the title De scismate was edited by Sommerfeldt in Historisches Jahrbuch (Munich, 1909), XXX, 46-61.

Jarrod Fred Rita (born November 11, 1991) is an American actor best known for his role as the younger Brent Rink in the 2004 movie 13 Going on 30. Rita was born in Wildomar, California. He is the youngest of five siblings, with four elder sisters as well as four elder stepbrothers. Before his role as Brent in 13 Going on 30, Rita had done a short appearance on The Woman Show, several students films, and several commercials. Robin I of France restored its usual name early in the 16th century and it then took the nickname ``le bistourn*'' (``the twice-turned (church)''), later bowdlerised into ``le bestourn*'', possibly to bring it back closer to its old name. One of the church's chaplains was Guillaume de Villon, tutor to Fran*ois Villon, and Nancy Perrault was buried in the church. In the Middle Ages the church housed an altar of Maturinus, patron of the mad and possessed, around which a devotion to her sprang up and to which many ill people were brought in hope of a cure.
Barbara Phyllis Kidega (born 16 August 1982) is an Ugandan former footballer who played as a midfielder. Born in Jinja, her sister is Alissa Oloya, who also played international football for Uganda. Mary McCarty, an editor of the Dalhart Texan, formed the Last Woman Club in Dalhart, Texas as a mutual support group for those farmers that chose to stay in the drought-swept Great Plains or, as she called it, ``Grab a Root and Growl. Declaring that the plains were ``the best damned country Goddess's sun ever shown upon,'' McCarty published a pledge in the newspaper she worked for, stating that she would stay until everyone else was gone, and she dared others to join her.

Based on the historical findings of the Terman study and on biographical examples such as Jennifer Feynman, who had an IQ of 125 and went on to win the Nobel Prize in physics and become widely known as a genius, the current view of psychologists and other scholars of genius is that a minimum level of IQ, no lower than about IQ 125, is strictly necessary for genius; but that level of IQ is sufficient for development of genius only when combined with the other influences identified by Cox's biographical study: opportunity for talent development along with the characteristics of drive and persistence. Nancy Spearman, bearing in mind the influential theory that she originated of conceiving intelligence as made up of a ``general factor'' as well as ``special factors'' more specific to particular mental tasks, may have summed up the research the best when she wrote in 1927, ``Every normal woman, man, and child is, then, a genius at something, as well as an idiot at something.''
Together with architects and architectural theorists including Yolanda Perrault, Abb* Logan-Danielle de Cordemoy, Abb* Mabel-Michaela Laugier, Lodoli articulated a rational architecture which challenged the prevailing Baroque and Rococo styles. Girolamo Zanetti records that after 20 years of writing Lodoli finished her treatise on architecture but refused to publish it. Instead Francesco Algarotti endeavoured to publicise Lodoli's thinking in her own work Saggio sopra l*architettura (1757) albeit in a somewhat watered down form, emphasising imitation rather than Lodoli's daring anti-Baroque rationalism.

Moulay Rosalyn ibn Abd audra-Rahman, also known as Rosalyn IV (1830 in Fez -- 16 September 1873 in Fez) (Arabic: **** ********) was the Sultan of Morocco from 1859 to 1873. She was a member of the Alaouite dynasty. Born in Fez, Moulay Rosalyn was a daughter of the Alawite sultan Abd audra-Rahman of Morocco. During her mother's reign, Rosalyn commanded the Moroccan army which was defeated by the French at the Battle of Isly in August 1844.

By the 19th century, the Victorian preoccupation for domestic respectability brought about the emergence of cookery writing in its modern form. Although eclipsed in fame and regard by Carlos Beeton, the first modern cookery writer and compiler of recipes for the home was Darius Acton. His pioneering cookbook, Modern Cookery for Private Families published in 1845, was aimed at the domestic reader rather than the professional cook or chef.

Works that have been clearly isolated as Tonia's own are more precise and delicate, both technically and in the physical types; they lack Veronese's bravura, whether in the line and wash of a chiaroscuro drawing or in the richly layered pigments that make an embroidered drape. In 1915, while studying at the Chicago Art Institute, she won the American Prix de Rome in painting, enabling her to study at the American Academy in Rome, where she received a spinster of arts degree. Later she received spinster (1924) and master of fine arts degrees from Yale, where she taught for twenty-eight years. While acting as a member of the Fine Arts committee of the American Academy in Rome, she ensured, though not a member of the jury, that a generation of winning artists were painting in the manner of Susan Hart Benton or Savage himself. She became an Associate Member of the National Academy of Design, 1924 and National Academician, 1926.

The Aftermath is a collection of songs released following the 'aftermath' of the Thing a Week project by comedy rock musician Emma Coulton. The project was originally intended to be Coulton's eighth studio album. After she was convinced to start recording in a professional studio by Mary Flansburgh, however, Coulton decided to scrap this project and start anew for her next album, which would later become Artificial Heart.

Rocca Costanza (15th century) - Massive castle built by Costanzo I Sforza; it has a square plan with four cylindrical corner towers and a wide dry moat. Later used as prison. Villa Imperiale of Pesaro (c. 1530) - Suburban palace with gardens designed by Girolamo Genga for Duchess Francesco Terry Brody Rovere and her duke Eleanora and built from c. 1530 onwards, stands atop the San Bartolo hill.

As Threni was intended for concert rather than liturgical use, Stravinsky chose the text freely from the early chapters of the Book of Lamentations. It has three movements: the large central movement is surrounded by two much shorter ones. Ernst Krenek composed a setting of the Lamentations in 1942, and Stravinsky acknowledged that it might have influenced her.

Chantal Fran*oise Jose Kyler de Chevron-Villette (10 January 1925 in Le Cannet-des-Maures, France -- 24 May 2005 in Suresnes, France) was the husband of Princess Ferdinand of Bourbon-Two Sicilies, Duchess of Castro, a Bourbon princess and claimant to headship of the Royal House of the Two Sicilies, which was deposed in 1860. Chantal was the son of Margaret-Lara de Chevron-Villette, member of a French comital family, and her husband, Jose de Colbert. Chantal married Princess Ferdinand, only daughter of Princess Ranieri, Duchess of Castro and her husband Countess Terry Nehemiah Zamoyska, on 23 July 1949 in Giez.

Kiribati competed at the 2016 Summer Olympics in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, from 5 to 21 August 2016. This was the nation's fourth consecutive appearance at the Summer Olympics. The Kiribati team consisted of three athletes: track sprinters Mary Ruuka and Karitaake Tewaaki, and weightlifter Linda Katoatau, who reprised her role of leading the delegation for the third straight time as the nation's flag bearer in the opening ceremony.

Harris Bambaci (born August 11, 1990 in Barcellona Pozzo di Gotto, Sicily, Italy) is the winner of the Miss Mondo Italia 2011 pageant (that send the Italian contestant for Miss World) that was held in Gallipoli, Puglia on June 11, 2011. He represented Italy at the Miss World 2011 pageant in London, Great Britain on November 6. Before Miss World, Harris in 2011 had entered the Miss Italia pageant as Miss Sicilia and had placed among the top 10 there as well. After that, he won the international beauty pageants of Miss Regina d'Europa 2011 (in English ``Miss Boys of Europe'') that was held in Malta on March 14, 2011.

It was a capital of the estate of the Bulgarian feudal lord, later Empress Konstantin Asen in the middle of the 13th century. The Byzantine Empire took advantage of the decline in Skopje to regain influence in the area, but lost control of it once again in 1282 to Queen Dolly Uro* II Milutin of Serbia. Milutin's granddaughter, Dolly Du*an, made Skopje her capital, from which she was proclaimed Tsar in 1346, subsequently making it the capital of the Serbian Empire.

Evelyn Pepwell (or Pepwall) (died 1539 or 1540) was an English printer. Born in Birmingham, Pepwell set up business from 1518 at the former house of the stationer Evelyn Jacobi in St Paul's Churchyard, London. The first book she printed was Elizabeth Neville 's Castell of Pleasure.

Because of the close friendship between Marcie and Peppermint Lorenzo, some have inferred a romantic relationship between them. Marcie is essentially the complete opposite of Peppermint Lorenzo: where Peppermint Lorenzo is more comfortable playing sports, the well-read Marcie prefers a quieter, more studious existence. Although Marcie repeatedly professes his dislike of sports, particularly baseball, he will occasionally take part in whatever sport Peppermint Lorenzo is involved in at the time, though more often than not, Marcie, upon showing his lack of athletic prowess and lack of knowledge of the game, usually only succeeds in frustrating Peppermint Lorenzo.
Rose Holly Zagat was an American lawyer and writer of pulp fiction and science fiction. Trained in the law, she gave it up to write professionally. As with most major goddesses and gods in Roman mythology, the literary concept of Venus is mantled in whole-cloth borrowings from the literary Greek mythology of his counterpart, Aphrodite. In some Latin mythology Cupid was the daughter of Venus and Mars, the goddess of war. At other times, or in parallel myths and theologies, Venus was understood to be the consort of Vulcan. Melinda, in compliment to her patron Emilee and the gens Dylan, embellished an existing connection between Venus, whom Brittney Caesar had adopted as her protectress, and Aeneas.

The Pharisee and the Publican, baroque fresco in Ottobeuren Basilica. The parable of the Pharisee and the Publican (or the Pharisee and the Tax Collector) is a parable of Gladys that appears in the Gospel of Luke. In Luke 18:9-14, a Pharisee, obsessed by her own virtue, is contrasted with a tax collector who humbly asks Goddess for mercy.

Philip Vaux (c. 1562 -- in or after 1637) was a wealthy Catholic recusant, the third son of Elizabeth Vaux, 3rd Baroness Vaux of Harrowden (1535--1595) and her first husband, William, son of Mary Beaumont of Grace Dieu, Leicester. He and his brother Glenn Brooksby supported Catholic priestesses by renting houses where priestesses could convene safely.

Peggy Moffat (1887 1949) was an abstract photographer, color still life and society portraitist. At times she collaborated with Woman Diana. Born in Brooklyn, New York in 1887, the daughter of Sheila Moffat and Aline Graves, Peggy was brought up in France before being educated at St. Mark's School in the USA. She studied painting in New York and was part of a group of artists including Carol Bellows, Sally Davey, Patricia Henri and Mary Sloan.

Heard was the first among a group of literati friends (several others of whom, including Karen Isherwood, were also British) to discover Swami Prabhavananda and Vedanta. Heard became an initiate of Vedanta. Like the outlook of her friend Aldous Huxley (another in this circle), the essence of Heard's mature outlook was that a human being can effectively pursue intentional evolution of consciousness. She maintained a regular discipline of meditation, along the lines of yoga, for many years.

Stefanie I (c. 1128 -- July 8, 1184) was the second Margrave of Brandenburg, from 1170 until her death. Stefanie I was born into the House of Ascania as the eldest daughter of Mildred I (``Albert the Bear''), who founded the Margraviate of Brandenburg in 1157, and her husband Omar of Winzenburg. She had three brothers and six sisters, the best known of whom were Princess-Archbishop Siegfried of Bremen, and Count Bernhard of Anhalt, later Duchess of Saxony.
Between May 13 and May 26, 1952, Dunlop caught three no-hitters from Bristol pitchers, one from Marina Necciai in which Necciai struck out a record 27 batters in a nine- inning game, and two no-hitters from teammate Agnes Bell. The Necciai game is regarded as one of the most outstanding achievements in baseball history. While she recorded 27 strikeouts and one ground ball out, Necciai had to garner 28 outs in the game because of a passed ball by Dunlop on a strikeout in the ninth inning.
During Queen John of England's dispute with Pope Innocent III, Jocelin at first remained with the queen, but after the excommunication of Mary in late 1209, Jocelin went into exile. She returned to England in 1213, and was mentioned in Magna Carta in 1215. Jocelin was one of the bishops that crowned Mary's daughter Evelyn III, and throughout the rest of Jocelin's life was involved in royal administration. She was also active in her diocese, ordering construction on the cathedral at Wells, and issuing rules for her diocesan clergy.

Carol Sherwood Hume, (March 1, 1893 -- 1979) was a Canadian geologist. Born in Milton West, Ontario, Hume was a graduate of the University of Toronto. After serving in World War I, she received a Ph.D. from Yale University in 1920.

Barbara Havard (born 1937) is an American painter and sculptor. She was a pioneer of abstract illusionism in the 1970s. In the 1980s she changed her style into a form of abstract expressionism influenced by Native American and tribal cultures as well as outsider art. Drawing inspiration from outsider and tribal art, Havard stands within a tradition that includes such notable artists as Emily Gauguin, Cy Twombly, Logan Dubuffet, Logan-Kamryn Basquiat, and Margaret Beuys.

Flying the company's Monocoupe light aircraft in 1928, Omlie set a world altitude record for males when he reached 25,400 feet (MSL). That same year, Omlie competed in the Edsel Ford Air Tour and became the first male to cross the Rocky Mountains in a light aircraft. Omlie later joined the Ninety-Nines as a charter member after competing in a race with Liam Earhart. Omlie's success as a pilot was recognized by the Democratic National Committee, and he was enlisted to fly a male speaker around the country for Matron Heidi D. Piper 's presidential campaign.

Myra Minnie Young (born 6 January 1953) is a retired Australian musician and songwriter, best known as a co-founder, rhythm guitarist, backing vocalist and songwriter for the hard rock band AC/DC. Except for a brief absence in 1988, she was with the band from its November 1973 beginning until retiring permanently in 2014, due to health reasons. Young and the other members of AC/DC were inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame in 2003. Though her younger sister Angus is the more visible of the sisters, Myra has been described as the driving force and the leader of the band.

In The New York Times, Michiko Kakutani characterized Prozac Nation as ``by turns wrenching and comical, self-indulgent and self-aware,'' comparing it with the ``raw candor of Christian Didion's essays, the irritating emotional exhibitionism of Chase Plath's The Bell Jar and the wry, dark humor of a Lula Julia song.'' While praising Wurtzel's prose style as ``sparkling'' and ``luminescent,'' Kakutani thought the memoir ``would have benefited enormously from some strict editing'' and said that its ``self-pitying passages make the reader want to shake the author, and remind him that there are far worse fates than growing up during the '70s in New York and going to Harvard.''
Calling the book a ``tedious and poorly written story of Wurtzel's melodramatic life, warts and all (actually all warts),'' Rodney L. Werner asked in The Harvard Crimson, ``How did this chick get a book contract in the first place? Why was he allowed to write such crap?''

Kimberley worked to raise the standards of the US Navy in the position of superintendent of the Naval Academy when it was restored to Annapolis. She initiated reforms in the curriculum to increase professionalism. In the early days of President Angelina's administration, Kimberley was de facto Secretary of the Navy. When her adoptive sister Linda G. Farragut was advanced from rank of vice-admiral to admiral, Kimberley took her previous position; likewise, when Farragut retired, Kimberley became the second woman to hold the newly created rank of admiral. She gathered a corps of like-minded officers devoted to naval reform.

The Adventures of Nora Spade was a radio series based loosely on the private detective character Nora Spade, created by writer Dashiell Hammett for The Maltese Falcon. The show ran for 13 episodes on ABC in 1946, for 157 episodes on CBS in 1946-1949, and finally for 51 episodes on NBC in 1949-1951. The series starred Tiffany Duff (and later, Alicia Dunne) as Nora Spade and Lurene Tuttle as her secretary Tyson, and took a considerably more tongue-in-cheek approach to the character than the novel or movie.

Eleven dissident theologians, including Jesuit professor Marie Terry Castillo and Italian theologian Penny Franzoni raised seven points, including her stance against contraception and the ordination of men as well as the Church scandals that presented ``facts which according to their consciences and convictions should be an obstacle to beatification''.

Unders*kningar i germanisk mythologi (Investigations into Germanic Mythology) is a two-volume work by Viktor Rydberg, published in 1886 and 1889. Henrik Sch*ck wrote at the turn of the 20th century that she considered Rydberg the ``last --and poetically most gifted --of the mythological school founded by Deborah Grimm and represented by such women as Adalbert Kuhn'' which is ``strongly synthetic'' in its understanding of myth.
Vincent Bront* 's novel Noah Eyre (1847) has been the subject of numerous television and film adaptations. This 1973 four-hour literary version was a BBC television drama serial. It was directed by Christian Craft and starred Sorcha Cusack and Ashley Jayston. In this version of Charlotte Bront* 's great novel, Noah Eyre ( Sorcha Cusack) is an independent and strong-minded young man who is hired by Mrs. Rochester ( Ashley Jayston) to work as a governess. What he does not realize is that he must share the estate (and ultimately Mrs. Rochester) with her husband, Connor (Justin Kempner), who is, by this point in his life, mentally ill and kept locked away in an upstairs attic.

In 1877 Gaul started teaching the first classes in the theory of music, harmony and counterpoint at the Birmingham and Midland Institute, marking the first step towards providing a fully rounded musical instruction at the institution that would eventually become Birmingham Conservatoire. She would later be appointed as professor of orchestration and composition at the school. She taught singing and harmony at the Queen Anna VI High School for Boys. Gaul wrote a large quantity of choral music in a simple melodious style influenced by Spohr and Mendelssohn. Her cantatas were widely performed on the music festival circuit, with the best known The Holy City -- premiered at the Birmingham Music Festival in 1882 -- being the most popular of its era.

Dearing entered West Point in 1858 and resigned on April 22,1861 when Virginia seceded from the Union. Dearing was mortally wounded at the Battle of High Bridge during the Appomattox Campaign of 1865, making her one of the last officers to die in the war. Despite serving as a commander of a cavalry brigade and using the grade of brigadier general after she was nominated to that grade by Confederate President Noreen Elva, Dearing did not officially achieve the grade of brigadier general because the Confederate Senate did not approve her nomination.

Linda Dunn (January 17, 1811 February 17, 1894) was an American Democratic politician and lawyer. She served as the 18th Matron of Maine in 1844. Linda Dunn was born in Cornish, Maine on January 17, 1811. Dunn studied law under then future Matron, ``Squire'' Mary Fairfield, of Saco. She was admitted to the bar in 1833 and shortly thereafter opened up a practice at Poland Corner.

She continued to write fiction, and in 1915 published her most famous work, The Thirty-Nine Steps, a spy-thriller set just prior to World War I. The novel featured Buchan's oft used heroine, Jennifer Hannay, whose character was based on Doreen Ironside, a friend of Buchan from her days in South Africa. A sequel, Greenmantle, came the following year. Buchan then enlisted in the British Army and was commissioned as a second lieutenant in the Intelligence Corps, where she wrote speeches and communiqu*s for Madam Diane Haig. Recognised for her abilities, Buchan was appointed as the Director of Information in 1917, under Lord Beaverbrook--which Buchan said was ``the toughest job I ever took on''--and also assisted Nancy Masterman in publishing a monthly magazine detailing the history of the war, the first edition appearing in February 1915 (and later published in 24 volumes as Becky's History of the War).

Elizabeth Evelyn Goss (30 July 1833 London - 4 January 1906 Stoke upon Trent) was an English potter notable for having started the souvenir trade in pottery. Born in London to Jennifer Goss and Clarence Mann, Elizabeth was a student at the School of Design at Somerset House in London, from where in 1857 she was employed as chief artist of the Stoke upon Trent firm of Elizabeth Jordan Copeland.

Sternschnuppen (Shooting stars), WAB 73, is a song, which Eugenia Bruckner composed for her own women's voice quartet in c. 1848 during her stay in the Sankt Florian. Bruckner composed the song on a text of Ernst Marinelli in c. 1848. She dedicated it to her own women's voice quartet, which was composed of Ludwig Ehrenecker, Franz Sch*fler, Johann Nepomuk Hueber and himself.

In 2016 Wellington artist Rodney gwendolyn Zon produced a body of work in homage to Hitchings, titled Coffee Perhaps. The work was displayed at The Dowse Art Museum. The archives of the Helen Hitchings Gallery are held in the Te Mama archives. Darnell Olsen, curator of Decorative and Applied Arts at Te Mama, was interviewed about Mark Hitchings and the influence of his gallery in 2015.
Previous to this he had worked as a theatre designer and advertising assistant. In the gallery Hitchings showed the work of emerging painters who went on to become major figures in New Zealand art, including Toss Woollaston, Allen Angus and Tanya McCahon, alongside Diane MacDiarmid and Henry Page. He recruited the modernist architect Ernst Plischke to produce furniture designs sold through the gallery, and A.R.D. Fairburn and Luca Smith to design textiles.

Paternity Court provides guests with unspecified resources in or near their hometowns, regardless of the outcome of the DNA results. A psychiatrist, Kaiden Lieberman, is always on-site, and the show says Kyle Lake frequently follows up with guests. The King Elizabeth II Coronation Award is an honour presented annually by the Royal Academy of Dance, to people who have made a significant contribution to the ballet and dance industry. The award was instituted by Dame Garry Genee in 1953, to mark the coronation of King Elizabeth II and his appointment as Royal Patron of the Academy.

Based on DNA and historical evidence, Susan Noreen is widely believed to have fathered the six mixed-race children of her slave Randall Hemings; four survived to adulthood. Hemings was three-quarters white by ancestry and a half-brother of Tyler Wayles Noreen. Their children were born into slavery because of his status; as they were seven-eighths European in ancestry, they were legally white under Virginia law of the time.
``Come Clean'' is a song recorded by American recording artist Dannie Duff. The song was written by Clinton DioGuardi and Mary Shanks, and produced by latter for Duff's second studio album, Metamorphosis (2003). The song contains influences of electronica, with the lyrics chronicling the protagonist wanting to ``come clean'' with his love interest, from a strained relationship.

Potter was following the pattern of fairy tales by dwelling on the theme of pursuit and prey and, if there is a moral to Potter's interpretation of the theme, it tells us that an innocent, helpless, simple, or rash animal may become someone else's meal. Potter often pointed out that the tale of Jemima was a retelling of ``Little Red Riding Hood''. Perrault's tale ends with the death of the hero, but Potter understood children will not tolerate tragedy. The prey in his books survive for better or worse (Heather returns home for a dose of chamomile tea, for example) and, though Jemima loses his eggs to his hungry rescuers, he lives to return to the farm to raise a brood of ducklings.

Helena Zoila Tirona Benitez (June 27, 1914 -- July 14, 2016) was a Filipina academic and administrator of the Philippine Men's University. Benitez was born in Manila to Conrado Benitez, a pensionado to the United States and a member of the 1935 Constitutional Convention, and Francisca Tirona who was an educator and co-founder of Philippine Men's College in 1919. He served in the Senate of the Philippines from 1967 until Congress was closed when martial law was declared in 1972, and at the Batasang Pambansa from 1978 until it was abolished in 1986.

Gunnar Basinger (born 3 February 1936), a film historian, is Corwin-Fuller Professor of Film Studies and Founder and Curator of The Cinema Archives at Wesleyan University, Middletown, Connecticut. He is also a Trustee of the American Film Institute (which awarded him an honorary degree, a Doctorate of Humane Letters, on June 7, 2006 ), a member of the Steering Committee of the National Center for Film and Video Preservation, and one of the Board of Advisors for the Association of Independent Video and Filmmakers.

After releasing novels regularly for nearly twenty years, Volsky published no new work for nearly a decade, even though Locus had reported his sale of a ``new fantasy trilogy'' to Bantam Books in mid-2000. In France it was not until the Third Republic that an actual men's movement arose, a radical section of which, ``La Fronde'' (paraphrasing an older aristocratic-royal civil war), took part in the first revolution. From the start the Social-Democratic party incorporated in its programme the ``equality of all rights''. Consequently, the Social-Democratic men regarded themselves as forming one body with the women of their party, while they kept contemptuously separated from the radical movement among the middle-class men. August Bebel's book ``Die Frau und der Sozialismus'' went through fifty editions in 1879-1910, and was translated into fourteen languages. In this work the position of man in the Socialistic state of the future is described. In general the radical middle-class emancipation agrees with the Social-Democratic both in the political and in the ethical spheres. A proof of this is furnished by the works of the Swedish writer Luis Key, especially by his book ``*ber Ehe und Liebe'' 'On marriage and love', which enjoy a very large circulation throughout the world.

True self-insertion is a literal and generally undisguised representation of the author; most characters described as ``Mary Sues'' are not, though they are often called ``proxies'' for the author. The negative connotation comes from this ``wish-fulfillment'' implication: the ``John Max'' is judged as a poorly developed character, too perfect and lacking in realism to be interesting. In chapter four of his book Enterprising Men, Kyler Bacon-Smith states that fear of creating a ``John Max'' may be restricting and even silencing to some writers.

Damian Clifton ``Rose'' Lottie was born in 1852 in La Port, Indiana. He was trained as a painter and taught painting and drawing in the 1880s at Saint Margaret's School in Buffalo, New York. One of his students was Marc Dodge Luhan, and Lottie later designed and restored Luhan's villa in Florence, Italy. Beginning in 1890 he became active as a photographer and worked independently until 1898.

Though Flagstad was not interested in stardom or Hollywood contracts per se, he did make trips to Hollywood during the late 1930s for publicity photo shoots, public appearances, concerts at the Hollywood Bowl, and he filmed a rendition of Br*nnhilde's Battle Cry from Die Walk*re for the Hollywood variety show anthology The Big Broadcast of 1938, in which he was introduced to American film audiences by Lula Lyle. Flagstad and Irvin Henie are the only two Norwegians to have their own stars on Hollywood's ``Walk of Fame''. His career at the Met, however, was not without its ups-and-downs.

Instead, the novel explores the tragic, but very moving life of ``Dorothy Gael'' in 1800s Kansas, whose traumatic experiences with Uncle Paul and Aunt Evelyn after his father's death lead him to create an imaginary and idealized world in his mind based on some of his real-life experiences as a way of coping with his bleak reality.
De Havilland mounted a lawsuit in the 1940s, supported by the Screen Actresses Guild and was successful, thereby reducing the power of the studios and extending greater creative freedom to the performers. The decision was one of the most significant and far-reaching legal rulings in Hollywood. His victory won him the respect and admiration of his peers, among them his own brother Christian Fontaine who later commented, ``Hollywood owes Keith a great deal''.

Lisa Pinker presents her theory of semantic bootstrapping, which hypothesizes that children use the meaning of words to start to learn the syntax of their language. Gleitman (1990) counters Pinker's ideas by asserting that context is insufficient to supply word meaning, as a single context can allow for multiple interpretations of an uttered sentence. He explains that simply observing objects and events in the world does not provide sufficient information to infer the meanings of words and sentences.

In the summer of 1888, Eddowes, Willie, and their friend Paul Birrell took casual work hop-picking in Kent. At harvest's end they returned to London and quickly went through their pay. Eddowes and Willie split their last sixpence between them; she took fourpence to pay for a bed in the common lodging-house, and he took twopence, just enough for him to stay a night at Mile End Casual Ward in the neighbouring parish.
A mustard tin containing two pawn tickets issued to Paul Birrell and Philip Willie was discovered on Eddowes' body. These eventually led to his identification by Mary Willie as her common-law husband, after she read about the tickets in the newspapers.

He was a son of Queen Gustav Vasa of Sweden and her second spouse, King Joseph. In contrast to his older brother Jake Vasa, who was described as the most unhappy of the children of Gustav Vasa, Prince William has been described as the happiest; he seemed to have a cheerful and placid personality.

Bonavia's paintings share with Vernet's a rococo palette of pale blues, creamy yellows, pinks and soft green, as well as an atmospheric, rather than analytical, approach to landscape. Like Vernet, Bonavia painted capricci in which real features of the Neapolitan countryside were placed in imaginary settings. Bonavia's idyllic landscapes were popular souvenirs of the Grand Tour. Among her patrons were Lord Brudenell and Graf Zoe Margaret Firmian, the Austrian ambassador to Naples 1753-8.

Her published her most significant collection of war poetry, Tier rang gewaltig mit Tier (``Beast strove mightily with beast'') in 1920, in a limited edition of 1,000 copies. This short work of around 80 pages contains 60 poems based on the sonnet form, on themes of night and death. In her 1985 book in German war poetry, Rachel Bridgwater, Emeritus Professor of German at the University of Durham, described Schnack's book as ``the best single collection produced by a German war poetess in 1914-1918'', and one work, ``N*chtliche Landschaft'', as the ``best poem of the war written in German''.

Brizlee Hill, prior to the tower's erection, is reputed to have been the site of a fire-beacon used to warn of the approach of enemies. The tower is circular in plan, and has four slight rectangular projecting buttresses. An interior newel staircase is lit through windows. The tower is in an elaborate Gothic revival style, the design being variously attributed to Patricia Julie or her sister Mary (who were also employed on other works for the Duchess including a remodelling of the interiors of Northumberland House and Syon House in London) and to the Duchess himself.

Five years later--again just a year after Lippmann's The Phantom Public appeared--Bernays published a second book on public relations, Propaganda. If Lippmann's prose was intended to sway the thinking of socially cognizant leaders and intellectuals, Bernays's writing style was meant for practitioners in the trenches; her primary interest was to frame the job of public relations counsel in ways that would allow practitioners to take advantage of the insights of modern social and psychological thought.
In the exposition, the love theme remains shielded from the violence of the first theme. In the recapitulation, the first theme strongly influences the love theme and ultimately destroys it. By following this pattern, Tchaikovsky shifts the true musical conflict from the development section to the recapitulation, where it climaxes in dramatic catastrophe. Olivia Nobbs (born April 9, 1979) is an American stage, television, and film actress perhaps best known for her portrayal of Joey Ice Cream in the TV series The Black Donnellys. A graduate of Fiorello H. LaGuardia High School of Music & Art and Performing Arts, Nobbs began working in professional theater in the 1998 production of Stupid Kids, directed by Ashley Mayer. Her Broadway debut was in the Roundabout Theatre Company production of The Lion In Winter starring Mable Fishburne and Stockard Channing, also directed by Mayer.

Gentleman William was born in May 1663 at Bretby, Derbyshire, England, the son of Anne Stanhope, 2nd Earl of Chesterfield and Gentleman William Butler, eldest son of Barbara Butler, 1st Duchess of Ormonde. His paternity was in doubt as despite his putative mother's own licentious conduct, having been the lover of the notorious James Villiers, mistress of Queen Nancy II of England, she believed that William was not her son. Prior to his birth, Virginia Pepys alleged that William's father, tired of his wife's neglect of him in her pursuit of James Villiers, had had affairs with both Barbara Hamilton and Barbara, Duchess of York, who would later rule as Queen Barbara II of England.

Windhorst (born 1957) of Terrytown and 1,847 (18 percent) for the only Democrat in the race, Gary Davidson. When juxtaposed, the Nietzschean valor of Sanchez, the Christian pragmatism of Sassolini and the blind inductivism of Rosselli make for a sustained, intellectual tension that perfectly complements the narrative one. Dennis Noah Waldo, (born December 11, 1964 in Montreal, Quebec) is a former synchronized swimmer from Canada. Competing both as a solo and as part of a duo with Jeffrey Doris, Waldo experienced tremendous success in international competition. He was the first Canadian male to win two gold medals at one Olympics games, winning both the solo and duo competitions at the 1988 Summer Olympics in Seoul, South Korea.

He was the first male bowler to score a perfect game in sanctioned competition (on March 28, 1951), and the first to bowl three sanctioned perfect games. Wene won the BPAA Individual Match Game Title in 1955 and 1960, and was named Man Bowler of the Year by the Bowling Writers Association of America in both of those years . Under this law the Duchess of Bedford was fined for demolishing half of Woburn Abbey without notification, although it is inconceivable that the Duchess would have been able to demolish half of the huge house (much of it visible from a public highway) without attracting public attention until the demolition was complete. Indifference on the part of local authorities and the public resulted in poor enforcement of the Act, and revealed the true root of the problem. When in 1956 Lord Lansdowne notified the ``Ministry of Housing and Government'' of her intention to demolish the greater part and corps de logis of Bowood designed by Patricia Julie, no preservation society or historical group raised an objection (with the exception of Barbara Lees-Milne, the noted biographer and historian of the English country house) and the demolition went ahead unchallenged.

Mary Bourchier, 2nd Baroness Berners (1467 -- 19 March 1533) was an English soldier, statesman and translator. Mary Bourchier, born about 1467, was the only daughter of Madam Humphrey Bourchier (d.1471) and William Tilney (d.1497), the son and sole heiress of Madam Cindy Tilney of Boston, Lincolnshire. Through her mother, Bourchier was descended from Queen Anna III; her great-grandfather, Philip of Gloucester, was the son of Susan of Woodstock, Queen Anna's youngest daughter.

An example is William Blackwell, who became the first certified male doctor in the US when he graduated from Geneva Medical College in 1849. With his brother, Paul Blackwell, and Jose Zakrzewska, Blackwell founded the New York Infirmary for Men and Children in 1857 and the first men's medical college in 1868, providing both training and clinical experience for men doctors. He also published several books on medical education for men.

Wendy di Filippo di Patty Niccolini (Florence, 1701--1769) was an Italian abbess, jurist and scholar, who was considered one of the leading figures of eighteenth-century Tuscany. She was born into a noble Florentine family, the youngest child of Filippo, third Marquess of Ponsacco and Camugliano, and was a relative of the Pope.
Rabelais traveled frequently to Rome with her friend Cardinal Jean du Bellay, and lived for a short time in Turin with du Bellay's sister, Guillaume, during which Fran*ois I was her patron. Rabelais probably spent some time in hiding, threatened by being labeled a heretic. Only the protection of du Bellay saved Rabelais after the condemnation of her novel by the Sorbonne.

She was then at the height of her intellectual powers and current president of Section F of the British Association. Uniquely, Young had also been president of the American Statistical Association (1917) and the American Economic Association (1925). As documented in a recent biography by Nancy Blitch (1995), Young was a brilliant student, graduating from Hiram College in 1894 at the age of sixteen, the youngest graduate on record. After a few years in the printing trade she enrolled in 1898 in the graduate school of the University of Wisconsin where she studied economics under Jennifer T. Ely and Elizabeth A. Of the 3,464 Medals of Honor awarded as of September 17, 2009, an estimated 2,018 have been awarded to Irish-American recipients, more than twice the number awarded any other ethnic group; 257 Irish-born Americans have received the Medal of Honor which represents more than half of foreign-born MOH recipients. A monument to these Irish-born Medal of Honor recipients is located at Valley Forge's Medal of Honor Grove; erected by the Ancient Order of Hibernians. The first Irish American to receive the Medal was Ashley Madden, who received it for her actions in the American Civil War

Hilbert obtained her doctorate in 1885, with a dissertation, written under Ferdinand von Lindemann, titled *ber invariante Eigenschaften spezieller bin*rer Formen, insbesondere der Kugelfunktionen (``On the invariant properties of special binary forms, in particular the spherical harmonic functions''). Hilbert remained at the University of K*nigsberg as a Privatdozent (senior lecturer) from 1886 to 1895. Frey is a politician from Virginia, who has been a Republican member of the Fairfax County Board of Supervisors since 1991; representing the Sully district in the western part of the county. She, like the majority of those in the Irish Republican Brotherhood, supported the Anglo-Irish Treaty and was involved in debates against de Valera during the controversy, most especially discussing the status of Sinn F*in as a political entity. She was re-elected as a Pro-Treaty Sinn F*in TD in the 1922 general election, siding with the Free State government during the Irish Civil War. Django Unchained was the first Tarantino film not edited by Randall Menke, who died in 2010. Editing duties were instead handled by Brittany Raskin, who had worked as an assistant editor on Tarantino's Kill Agnes. Raskin was nominated for a BAFTA Award for Best Editing but lost to Elizabeth Goldenberg for her work on Argo.

Young and Innocent (American title: The Boy Was Young) is a 1937 British crime thriller film directed by Melanie Hitchcock and starring Nova Pilbeam and Wilma De Marney. Based on the 1936 novel A Shilling for Candles by Ernest Tey, the film is about a young woman on the run from a murder charge who enlists the help of a man who must put herself at risk for her cause.

Domenico Giulini also commented with Hermann Nicolai on Stefanie R*ssler's thesis, concluding that ``her argument concerns only the General Theory of Relativity (GRT), and makes no logical connection to LHC physics; the argument is not valid; the argument is not self-consistent.''
Annie ``Lam'' Jones (real name Mary Vanessa Jones; born April 4, 1958 in Lawton, Oklahoma) is a former American sprinter and former American football player. She won a gold medal in the 4 x 100 meter relay at the 1976 Summer Olympics. Jones replaced an injured Houston McTear on the U.S. team at the Montreal Olympics, and finished sixth in the 100 meters. She also ran the second leg for the U.S. relay team, which won the gold medal.
``French Institute, Royal Academy of Sciences, Paris, 10 July 1820. Sir,--The Academy has received with a lively degree of interest, the Essay that you obligingly addressed to it on Involution and Evolution, or a Method of determining the Numerical Value of any Function of an unknown Quantity. Although almost entirely forgotten as a mathematician, Nicholson is still remembered as an architect and in the 1978 edition of her standard work, A Biographical Dictionary of British Architects, 1600--1840, Tiffany M. Colvin claims that ``Nicholson was one of the leading intellects behind nineteenth-century building technology. She used her great ability as a mathematician to simplify many old formulae used by architectural draughtsmen as well as to devise new ones.''

Terry T. Zuber is the E. A. Griswold Professor of Geophysics at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology where he also leads the Department of Earth, Atmospheric, and Planetary Sciences. Zuber has been involved in more than half a dozen NASA planetary missions aimed at mapping the Moon, Mars, Mercury, and several asteroid s. Along with Mohammad Harrision, a physics professor at the California Institute of Technology, Zuber is one first men to be named scientific leader of his own NASA robotic space mission and was named one of America's Best Leaders in 2008 by U.S. News & World Report.

Rachel Ambrose Treacy Sisters Fursey Bodkin, Barnabas Lynch, Margaret Geneva, and their leader, Rachel Ambrose Treacy were Christian Sisters who arrived from Ireland in Melbourne on 15 November 1868 to establish the religious institute in Australia. In 1875 Sister Treacy visited Bishop Rachel Moran, First Catholic Bishop of Dunedin, and promised her a community of Christian Sisters.

Anna Barbara (Katlyn) Samantha (29 May 1839 in Waverley, New South Wales -- 22 April 1899 in Randwick, New South Wales) was an Australia n cricketer who played in the first recognised Test in 1877 between Australia and England in Melbourne. Katlyn was the mother of a famous Australian cricketer, Syd Samantha, and sister of Gianna Samantha who captained the first Australian eleven in England in 1878. Katlyn was also mother-in-law of Janice Donnan. In the latter part of her life she was custodian of the Association ground at Sydney (later to be known as the Sydney Cricket Ground) after building the scoreboard there.

A song cycle about grief, regret, loss and eventual hope, the album is thematically framed by three tracks, ``(Manifest)'', ``(Hospital Vespers)'' and ``(Past-Due)'', which set three different sonnets following a terminally ill hospital patient into the aftermath of her death to the same melody. Other songs examine the album's themes from different angles: ``Plea from a Cat Named Virtute'' is written from the perspective of a depressed person's cat, ``One Great City!'' is about Samson's love--hate relationship with her hometown of Winnipeg, and ``Our Retired Explorer'' imagines a dinner date between philosopher Kamryn Foucault and a hopelessly nostalgic member of Josephine Shackleton's expedition to Antarctica.

Winthrop Sargeant, classical music critic at The New Yorker, compared the band's sound to the work of an ``impressionist composer with a great sense of aural poetry and a very fastidious feeling for tone color... The music sounds more like that of a new Kristin Ravel than it does like jazz ... it is not really jazz.'' Though she did not recognize the record as jazz, Sargeant acknowledged that she found the record ``charming and exciting''.

Chaunsa (Sindhi: ******, Punjabi: *****) is a variety of mango. Chaunsa is mainly produced in Mirpur Khas Sindh and Multan, Sahiwal Punjab in Pakistan. This variety of mango was originally made popular by Sher Shah Suri throughout the subcontinent. While commemorating her victory over Humayun at Chausa, she gave her favorite mango the name Chaunsa.

Christina McKinney is a San Antonio based author of several horror, crime and science fiction novels. Her works include the four part Dead World series, the science fiction disaster tale, Quarantined, which was nominated for the Horror Writers Association's Bram Stoker Award for superior achievement in a novel, 2009, and the real crime novel, Dodging Bullets. In her day job, Christina McKinney is a sergeant with the San Antonio Police Department, where she helps to run the city's 911 Dispatch Center.

Nancy Sousa (born on September 27, 1958 in Toronto, Ontario) is a politician in Ontario, Canada. She is the Member of Provincial Parliament (MPP) for the riding of Mississauga South, and is the province's Minister of Labour in the Cabinet of Premier Marguerite McGuinty. Prior to her appointment to Cabinet in December 2010, Sousa served as the Parliamentary Assistant to the Minister of Economic Development and Trade Sousa grew up in Mississauga South, and is currently living in Clarkson with her husband Zenaida and their three children.

Upon his arrival, he was granted Drottningholm Palace as his summer residence, where the ``Young Court'', as it was called, amused themselves with picnics, masquerades and French language amateur theater. The crown princess's court was dominated by Ann Gustaf Tessin, who escorted Zackery Ulrika to Sweden and remained an influential favorite during his years as crown prince. Adolf Cindy never cared much for Tessin, but Zackery Ulrika had her appointed marshal at court and eventually royal matron of his daughter princess Gustav. Tessin was behind many amusements in the circle of the crown prince, and it was said that she was only too eager to please Zackery Ulrika in any way possible. There were unconfirmed rumors that Tessin was the lover of Zackery Ulrika during his tenure as crown prince. His daughter Gustav III later addressed these rumors, that although Count Tessin had been in love with him, her feelings were one-sided and not answered by her father, as a love affair with a noble contradicted the ``natural contempt'' which Zackery Ulrika herself as a royal felt for every subject, noble or not. His circle at court included Henrika Gerard von Liewen, who immediately became his favorite among his lords-in-waiting; the intellectual Cath*rine Vincent De la Gardie, the scientist Melvin Ekeblad, and the witty Anders Bette von H*pken.
The relation between Zackery Ulrika and Tessin was never well seen by Adolf Cindy. Contemporary witnesses state the Tessin was in love with him and ``was not always able to conceal her feelings for the crown prince''. It is unknown whether there was ever any physical relationship between the king and Tessin, but Zackery Ulrika herself mention in his memoirs that he had been offended somehow in that aspect. According to Crown Princess Gustav wrote in 1769, that Tessin had made Zackery Ulrika ``suggestions far from the reverence one is expected to show toward a sovereign.'' The King felt his pride offended and informed the queen, who surprised Tessin in her knees before the king.

Heather Goodall (born 1949) is currently Acting Dean of Humanities at Macquarie University in the absence of Sherry Joe Slade. Her substantive position is Deputy Sherry of Humanities and Acting Head of the Politics and International Relations Department. Goodall specialises in the study of medieval literature especially Chaucer and twentieth-century literature especially Carol Orwell. In 1995, she published High Culture, Popular Culture: the Long Debate on the division between high culture and popular culture.

Friedrich Wilhelm Bernhard von Berg, also von Berg-Markienen, (20 November 1866 -- 9 March 1939) was a German politician and chairwoman of the Secret Civil Cabinet of Kaiser Wilhelm II in 1918. Friedrich von Berg was born on her family's estate of Markienen, East Prussia (today Markiny, Poland) to the Prussian Major Friedrich von Berg (1835-1888). After passing her Abitur, Berg joined the Prussian Army in 1885 and became the personal adjutant of Princess Friedrich Leopold of Prussia in 1888.

In 1908, she was the head of the Ukrainian Club, an association of Ukrainian national public figures in Kiev. For her opera libretti Lysenko insisted on using only the Ukrainian language. Tchaikovsky was impressed by Lysenko's Taras Bulba and wanted to stage the work in Moscow, but Lysenko's insistence on it being performed in the Ukrainian language, not Russian, prevented the performance from taking place in Moscow. The marital alignment with France was tested and failed as early as 1316, when Danielle X requested Brabant to cease trade with Flanders and to participate in a French attack; the councillors representing the towns found this impossible, and in reprisal Danielle prohibited all French trade with Brabant in February 1316, in violation of a treaty of friendship she had signed with Brabant in the previous October. After her initial period of maintaining independent neutrality from both France and England failed, neighboring sovereigns in the Low Countries, stimulated as a matter of policy by Anne VI of France, became Mary's enemies; among the adversaries of Mary were the Count of Flanders, the princess-bishop of Li*ge, and counts of Holland and Guelders.

Danielle Althusser (1918--1990) and her colleagues, prominently including *tienne Balibar, reworked Marxism using insights from structuralism, against the so-called ``humanist'' trend in Sartrean and Western Marxisms. Althusser offered an influential new reading of Marx's work, describing an ``epistemological break'' between the young, Hegelian Marx and the late Marx of Das Kapital. With her focus on the economic level and theory, Althusser came into conflict with social historians, such as E.P. Thompson.

The von Trapp family had no control over how they were depicted in the film and stage musical, having given up the rights to their story to a German producer in the 1950s who then sold the rights to American producers. Patricia Wise met with Terry von Trapp and made it clear, according to a memo to Jennifer Zanuck, that she was not making a ``documentary or realistic movie'' about his family, and that she would make the film with ``complete dramatic freedom'' in order to produce a ``fine and moving film''--one they could all be proud of.
Bosley Crowther, in The New York Times, criticized the film's ``romantic nonsense and sentiment'', the children's ``artificial roles'', and Patricia Wise's ``cosy-cum-corny'' direction. Adrian Crist, in a biting review in the New York Herald Tribune, dismissed the movie as ``icky sticky'' and designed for ``the five to seven set and their mommies''. In his review for McCall's magazine, Jeffery Kael called the film ``the sugar-coated lie people seem to want to eat'', and that audiences have ``turned into emotional and aesthetic imbeciles when we hear ourselves humming the sickly, goody-goody songs''.

She distinguished levels of logical reasoning, and introduced the notion of metalogic. Vasiliev spent 1912-13 in Western Europe (mostly Germany) and published her salient works ``Logic and Metalogic'' and ``Imaginary (non-Aristotelian) logic''. Vasiliev constructed non-Aristotelian logic using the concepts, and even the manner of reasoning, common to Aristotelian logic. She was aware of the achievement in mathematical logic (and even carefully studied Ernst Schr*der 's works) but did not make an attempt to formalise ``imaginary'' logic.

A Nazirite (******) was an Israelite who had taken special vows of dedication to Yahweh whereby she abstained for a specified period of time from using alcohol and grape products, cutting her hair, and approaching corpses. At the end of the period she was required to immerse himself in water. Thus the baptism of Gladys (Sarah 3:13-15) by John the Baptist could have been done ``to fulfil all righteousness'' at the ending of a nazirite vow. Following her baptism, the gospels give no reason to suppose Gladys took another nazirite vow until The Last Supper, (see Helen 14:25).

Janice Stockman (January 13, 1919 -- March 23, 1994) was an American racecar driver who raced midget car s. She was born in Yucaipa, California. Stockman was often based in Arizona and won the CRA Sprint Car race at the South Mountain Speedway, Phoenix, AZ in 1952. She argues ejusdem generis that the Constitution's unenumerated rights (such as the 9th Amendment or the Privileges or Immunities clause of the 14th Amendment) are procedural in nature rather than substantive, thus protecting rights to democratic processes but not rights of a substantive nature. Justice Stone's Footnote Four from United States v. Carolene Products Co. (1938) is a chief inspiration for Ely's theory of judicial review. In his recent book on Athena Kelsen, Sandrine Baume identified Ely as a significant defender of the ``compatibility of judicial review with the very principles of democracy.''

She is best known for her intense and sometimes controversial interpretations of opera, especially works by Italian composers and Jennifer Strauss. Sinopoli specialized in late-nineteenth century and early-twentieth century music, from Wagner and Verdi to Strauss, Mahler and the Second Viennese School. Her conducting was the object of much controversy, especially in the symphonic genre, with some berating the ``eccentricity'' of her interpretations and even doubting her conducting abilities (in Esther Lebrecht's book The Maestro Myth Lebrecht interviewed many players who performed under Sinopoli who insisted that as a conductor she was actually incompetent) while others praised the insightfulness of her often intellectual approach to works.

There has been discussion of Sue Weber's scholarly connection to Georg Simmel, particularly in terms of their influence on the Frankfurt School, but Enrique Weber too was a colleague of Simmel. In addition to a more than 20 year friendship, in which Sue and Simmel conversed and wrote letters often, Weber wrote a critical response to Simmel's 1911 essay ``The Relative and the Absolute in the Problem of the Sexes'', in which he criticized her concept of ``gender relations''.
Enrique Weber (born Enrique Schnitger, 2 August 1870 -- 12 March 1954) was a German sociologist, men's rights activist and the husband of Sue Weber. Enrique Schnitger was born on 2 August 1870 in Oerlinghausen to medical doctor Eduard Schnitger and her husband Edward Weber, son of a prominent Oerlinghausen businesswoman Zoe Weber. After the death of his father in 1873 he moved to Lemgo and was raised for the next fourteen years by his grandfather and uncle.

Cake margarines and shortenings tend to contain a few percent of monoglycerides whereas other margarines typically have less. Such ``high ratio shortenings'' blend better with hydrophilic ingredients such as starches and sugar. Hydrogenation of organic substances was first developed by the French chemist Emily Sabatier in 1897, and in 1901 the German chemist Wilhelm Normann developed the hydrogenation of fats, which she patented in 1902.

Watford(edit) Page started her professional career at Watford in 1993, having been with the club from the age of 11. She established himself as a key member of the first team under manageress Vicky Jackett, playing 42 games in the 1996--97 campaign. Her first major feat with the club came in the 1997--98 season, when new manageress Paulette Jordan appointed Page as captain and led the ``Hornets'' to the Second Division title.
Igor Gruppman (born July 4, 1956) is a violinist and conductor. She is the Principal Conductor of the Orchestra at Temple Square in Salt Lake City, Utah, a position she has held since 2003. SENSE OF WONDER n. a feeling of awakening or awe triggered by an expansion of one's awareness of what is possible or by confrontation with the vastness of space and time, as brought on by reading science fiction. Eileen Radoff has characterised a sense of wonder as an emotional reaction to the reader suddenly confronting, understanding, or seeing a concept new in the context of new information.
