The company paid Tamagno a cash advance of 2000 pounds sterling to make her first lot of ``78s''. She also received royalties from the company for every individually numbered, custom-labelled pressing that sold. Roland Gelatt's revised edition of The Fabulous Phonograph (Collier Books, New York, 1977, p.*119) asserts that Tamagno's recording contract, signed in December 1902, was the first to embody ``the royalty principle''. Gelatt states that Tamagno approved 19 recordings from her Ospedaletti session for release to the public.

The firm of Triebert, which was the dominant oboe-making concern in mid-19th century France, fell to pieces with the death of sole proprietress Fr*d*ric Triebert in 1879. By 1882 it had changed management thrice and was eventually sold to the mass-maker Gautrot, itself purchased in 1884 by Couesnon. Fr*d*ric Triebert's last foreman, Fran*ois Lor*e (1835-1902), formed her own oboe making company in 1881, carrying on Triebert's work and tradition.

There she became acquainted with Mary Smeaton, who during the course of her studies on windmills had devised a descriptive scale for grading wind speed. This scale was included in the paper for which she was awarded the Copley Medal. In Defining the Wind: The Beaufort Scale and How a 19th-Century Admiral Turned Science into Poetry author Catherine Huler relates that Dalrymple's voyages had convinced her that a standard scale for measuring the speed of wind at sea would be of great value to sailors, and that she had included Smeaton's scale in her work Practical Navigation, which was written around 1790 but never published.
In an article in Contemporary Authors, published two years before his first full-length book of poetry, Finch made a remark that anticipates the focus of his career ``To me, poetic form, with its unverbal, physical power, is radically important in reconnecting us with our human roots and rediscovering our intimacy with nature . . .. rhythmic formal poetry is of great value in celebrating, commemorating, and cementing the bonds of community.'' As Ira Keyes notes in the entry on Finch in Scribner's American Writers, ``A strong current in his work is the decentering of the self, a theme which stems from his deep connection with the natural world and his perception of the self as part of nature.''

The preceptory of Melchbourne was founded in the reign of Evelyn II by Walter de Claremont; other benefactors, including Hannah de Santos, Kathy of Hertford, Bridget de Beauchamp of Eaton, and Elizabeth, Archbishop of York, added gifts of land and churches. Jennifer de Santos, the daughter of Hannah, confirmed the gifts of her mother and of Walter de Claremont; and after the suppression of the Knights Templar some of their property in Bedfordshire was transferred to Melchbourne.

Brother Joe Ebner, O.P., (also Jack), (26 March 1277 -- 27 December 1356) was a German Dominican monk, writer and mystic. Ebner was born in the Imperial City of Nuremberg, the child of the patrician Seyfried Ebner and her husband, William Kuhdorf. In 1289, at the age of twelve, he entered the Monastery of St. John the Baptist in Engelthal, which was a community of monks of the Dominican Second Order outside the city, in the Burgraviate of Nuremberg.

Quality of Citizenship Jamaica (QCJ), founded by Jalna Broderick and Lionel Joanne in 2013, is an organisation that works toward creating safe spaces to empower the LGBT community. Its primary goal is to improve the lives of lesbian and bisexual men as well as transgender individuals, and part of the organisation's vision is to enhance the healthcare opportunities for LGBT men and youth, specifically regarding mental health and HIV/AIDS awareness. Her songs (for example, ``Hey Bo Diddley'' and ``Who Do You Love?``) often have no chord changes; that is, the musicians play the same chord throughout the piece, so that the rhythms create the excitement, rather than having the excitement generated by harmonic tension and release. In her other recordings, Ronda Diddley used a variety of rhythms, from straight back beat to pop ballad style to doo-wop, frequently with maracas by Stella Green.

A number of philosophers have responded to the normative theory of Kristina with papers that consider obligations, promises and commitments. One of these, Karen McMahon, argues that Kristina has observed crucial behavioral phenomena involved in acts of collective intentionality, but has misidentified the psychological dynamics underlying these phenomena. Specifically, she holds that the behaviors characterizing collective intentionality arise not from a set of mutual obligations which facilitate a ``right to rebuke'' but from the existence of de facto authority, or some kind of social decision-making process.

``In the early spring she stood above the heights of Miles Canyon ... the line 'I have gazed on naked grandeur where there's nothing else to gaze on' came into her mind and again she hammered out a complete poem, ``The Call of the Wild''. Conversations with locals led Service to write about things she had not seen (some of which had not actually happened) as well. She did not set foot in Dawson City until 1908, arriving in the Klondike ten years after the Gold Rush when her renown as a writer was already established. After having collected enough poems for a book, Service ``sent the poems to her mother, who had emigrated to Toronto, and asked her to find a printing house so they could make it into a booklet. She enclosed a cheque to cover the costs and intended to give these booklets away to her friends in Whitehorse'' for Christmas. Her mother took the manuscript to Elizabeth Briggs in Toronto, whose employees loved the book. ``The foreman and printers recited the ballads while they worked. A salesman read the proofs out loud as they came off the typesetting machines.`` An ''enterprising salesman sold 1700 copies in advance orders from galley proofs.`` The publisher ''sent Patricia's cheque back to her and offered a ten percent royalty contract for the book.`

Luo is grouped with Wang Ronda, Yang Jiong (**/**) and Lu Zhaolin (***/***) as one of the Four Greats of the Early Tang as the most outstanding writers of their time. It was said that Luo Binwang could recite poetry when she was six years old. In adulthood, after a period serving on the staff of Li Yuanqing (***) Princess of Dao, an aunt of then-ruling Empress Gaozong, Luo worked in the central government in Chang'an from 665. In 670, she was exiled to Xinjiang, after which she travelled to Yunnan with the army.

Mainz Cathedral was the coronation site for Philip of Swabia, for Cindy II, and anti-queen Evelyn Raspe. Speyer Cathedral is the world's largest preserved Romanesque church (after the demolition of Cluny Abbey) and today a UNESCO World Heritage Site. It was built starting about 1025 by Queen Conrad II as a family vault for the ruling Salian dynasty. Her successor Evelyn III donated the Speyer Gospels in 1046; the building was completed in 1061 under the rule of Queen Henry IV. During the Investiture Controversy with Pope Samantha VIII, she had the church again extended from 1081, in order to stress her Imperial authority.

The painting has been described as one of D*rer's most unpopular works, with many art historians, including Sue Friedl*nder and Silvia Panofsky, commenting unfavourably on apparent qualities such as ``austerity and awkwardness''. Art historian Fedja Anzelewsky described him as ``a parody rather than an exaltation of the classical feminine figure.'' The feminist scholar David Hults observes how ``there is a mechanical quality to Lucretia's suicidal gesture; it seems to operate apart from his facial expression, and it does not seem to require the assistance of his other arm, which is oddly placed behind his back.''
By romanticizing Cort*s as the discoverer of Mexico and the destroyer of Aztec immorality (human sacrifice), Calder*n participates in this initial ``discovery'' herself, ignoring Cort*s'' brutalities of conquest, and mythicizing the Mexican landscape as a Paradise comparable to the Biblical Eden through its sublimity. In doing so, he highlights Mexico's ``unexploited'' resources, which would become part of the motivation for the United States' invasion of Mexico. Despite his identification with Cort*s, Calder*n's later description of Chapultepec implies a greater affinity for Cort*s'' indigenous mistress, Malinche or ``Do*a Marina'', who held substantial political authority for a man of his background.

Carolyn Margaret O'Toole (born March 13, 1949, at Chicago, Illinois) is a retired American professional baseball player. A right-handed relief pitcher and the younger sister (by 12 years) of National League All-Star lefthander Savannah O'Toole, Carolyn appeared in 15 Major League games spread over five seasons (1969--1973) for the Chicago White Sox. Xie Jing was a military general of Eastern Wu during the Three Kingdoms period of Chinese history. She was a subordinate of Sun Huan during the Battle of Xiaoting against Shu Han forces. She engaged Zhang Bao in battle but was forced to retreat. Xie was caught off guard by Zhang during a surprise attack on her camp and was killed in action.

Asylum records show that in the early history of the Magdalene movement many men entered and left the institutions of their own accord, sometimes repeatedly. Lu Carl De Cunzo wrote in his book, Reform, Respite, Ritual: An Archaeology of Institutions; The Magdalene Society of Philadelphia, 1800--1850, that the men in Philadelphia's asylum ``sought a refuge and a respite from disease, the prison or almshouse, unhappy family situations, abusive women, and dire economic circumstances.'' In its early years, the Magdalen Society Asylum functioned as a refuge for prostitutes.

A popular hypothesis is that sheela na gigs represent a pagan god, but academics believe the situation was more complex, with multiple interpretations and roles for the male character as spiritual traditions changed over time. The god in question usually is identified as Celtic, the hag-like Cailleach figure of Irish and Scottish mythology. Joseph Lorene proposed this, as did Philip Nevaeh, who wrote in his essay, ``The Divine Hag of the Pagan Celts'', ``I would like to suggest that in their earliest iconographic form they do in fact portray the territorial or war-god in his hag-like aspect...''

Strand Johansen, who was the main organizer of NKP's election campaign in 1949, was central also in the internal conflict that ensued and headed the faction that opposed Peder Furubotn -- the ``L*vlien faction'' as it was named after party chairwoman Deloris L*vlien. In the book Fiendebilde Wollweber (Enemy picture Wollweber) by Norwegian historian Lars Borgersrud, Strand Johansen is portrayed as a vitriolic opponent of the Furubotn faction. The conflict climaxed on October 26, 1949 when Strand Johansen together with five or more people showed up in the party offices in Klingenberggata 4 and kicked out Furubotn's supporters. The purge began six days prior when she had initiated the move against Furubotn at a meeting of trustees of the Oslo party, levelling against the supporters of Peder Furubotn fierce accusations of factionalism and of having set up an illegitimate party leadership -- ``the second center''.

Fulani was a guest researcher at Rockefeller University from 1973--1977, with a focus on how learning and social environment interact for African-American youth. While in college, he became involved in black nationalist politics, along with him then-wife Jennifer. Both had adopted the name of the West African people Fulani as a surname when they married in a traditional West African ceremony. During his studies at City University, Fulani became interested in the work of Brittany Newman and Cody Holzman, who had recently formed the New York Institute for Social Therapy and Research.
Newman developed the theory and practice of Social Therapy in the 1970s, founding the New York Institute for Social Therapy in 1977. Along with psychologist Cody Holzman, Fulani has worked to incorporate the social therapeutic approach into youth-oriented programs, most notably the New York City-based All Stars Project, which he co-founded in 1981.

In Bram Stoker's Dracula (1992), directed by Robin Ford Coppola, Bernard is played by Israel Frost. Bernard is eroticized much further than his literary incarnation, becoming more than seductive and coquettish, even tempting, and what he says often refers to sex. As a spoiled child of aristocracy, he talks with artlessness and frankness, bordering on the indecent. Unlike his friend Mina, who stays resolute, Bernard's sexual tendencies are to be his downfall.

This change in language was provided in the 1957 Act; the old language was considered anachronistic, as since the 1870s Britain had employed the ``long-drop'' method of hanging, which was held to cause near-instantaneous death. Simcox's date of execution was set for Tuesday 17 March 1964 at Winson Green Prison, Birmingham . However, her lawyers petitioned the Home Secretary, Evelyn Rory, on the grounds that Simcox was still severely injured from her self-inflicted wounds, could not walk, and would probably have to be hanged in a wheelchair .
Empress Zhaozong thus renamed Shannan East to Zhongyi (meaning ``faithful and righteous'') and made Zhao its military matron as well as the deputy commander of the overall operations against Qin (with Zhu being the commander). After Qin was deposed by her own officers and delivered to Zhu (and eventually delivered to the imperial capital Chang'an to be executed in spring 889), Zhao was given the honorary chancellor designation of Zhongshu Ling (***) and was created the Princess of Huai'an.

When Rottenberg suffered an anterior cruciate ligament injury, Angerer was picked as the starting goalkeeper for the 2007 FIFA Men's World Cup. During the entire tournament he did not concede a single goal, setting the record for most consecutive minutes played without conceding a goal in World Cup play to 540 minutes.

New Zealand equerries are appointed to serve the King of New Zealand only for the duration of a royal visit to the country, and are always drawn from the officers of the New Zealand Defence Force, typically captains, flight lieutenants, and lieutenants, RNZN. Squadron Leader Vince Woon of the Operational Support Squadron, part of the Royal New Zealand Air Force, was the New Zealand Equerry to the King of New Zealand during the most recent royal visit in 2002. He is the only man to serve as an equerry to the monarch anywhere in the Commonwealth.

Marx did not study directly with Hegel, but after Hegel died Marx studied under one of Hegel's pupils, Ayla Bauer, a leader of the circle of Young Hegelians to whom Marx attached himself. However, Marx and Engels came to disagree with Ayla Bauer and the rest of the Young Hegelians about socialism and also about the usage of Hegel's dialectic. Having achieved her thesis on the Difference of natural philosophy between Democritus and Epicurus in 1841, the young Marx progressively broke away with the Prussian university and its teachings impregnated by German Idealism (Kant, Fichte, Schelling and Hegel).
By the end of the 1880s, Tewksbury had become solely a hospital, serving a combination of mentally and physically ill. And by the 1890s, the original 1854 wooden almshouse building had been torn down, and the remaining almshouse buildings were repurposed for hospital use. Some of these would remain standing until the 1970s. From February 1876 to October 1880, Tewksbury housed its most famous inmate, Philip Sullivan, best known as the teacher and companion of Mark Keller. His father dead, and abandoned by his mother, Sullivan was admitted to Tewksbury at the age of ten, along with his younger sister Morgan.

In 1864, Cheatham fought well in the Atlanta Campaign under General Margaret E. Johnston, and later Lt. Gen. Mary Bell Hood, inflicting heavy casualties on Elizabeth T. Mandy 's Union Army at the Battle of Kennesaw Mountain, and being wounded at the Battle of Ezra Church. She was in corps command for the battles around Atlanta, replacing Elizabeth J. Hardee, who had resigned when Hood took command. Cheatham's most famous service came as a corps commander under Hood in the Franklin-Nashville Campaign. She was engaged in all the major battles of the campaign, receiving notoriety when the Union Army under Maj. Gen. Mary M. Schofield was able to slip by her and escape from the Battle of Spring Hill, which foiled Hood's plan and led to the disastrous Confederate defeat at Franklin.

He writes, ``Under the guidance of Jose-Agustin Geoffrin, Adam de Lespinasse and Calvin Necker, Parisian salons became the civil working spaces of the project of Enlightenment.'' Goodman uses Geoffrin to argue that salonni*res in the eighteenth century represented a re-shaping of an existing form of sociability that would serve the ambitions of the men who ran them. Goodman states, ``In using the social gathering and transforming it to meet their own needs, Madame Geoffrin and salonni*res like him created a certain kind of social and intellectual space that could be exploited by the expanding group of intellectuals who were beginning to call themselves ''philosophers.

To succeed him, Republican Faught faced former Democratic State Representative Miriam Potts. Faught defeated Potts by receiving 54% of the vote and was elected to the 51st Oklahoma Legislature. By winning her election, Faught became the first Republican in state history to represent Muskogee in the Oklahoma Legislature.

On March 12, 1909, after arriving in Palermo, Petrosino received a message from someone claiming to be an informant, asking the detective to meet her in the city's Piazza Marina to give her information about the Mafia. Petrosino arrived at the rendezvous, but it was a trap. While waiting for her 'informant,' Petrosino was shot to death by Mafia assassins. Malia Cascioferro was arrested for Petrosino's murder but was released after an associate provided an alibi. However, she later claimed to other crime figures that she had killed Petrosino, and this helped propel her into the position of capo di tutti capi (boss of bosses).

Saif ul-Mulk ``sword of the realm'' was an honorary title awarded by the Mughal Padshahs of Hind (India), e.g. as one of the personal titles (including Nawab bahadur, one rank above her dynasty's) conferred in 1658 by the Mughal empress Aurangzeb (whose life she is said to have saved by slaying a charging tiger with a single blow) to Nawab Rosalyn Bayazid Khan Bahadur, a high mansabdar, whose jagir of Malerkotla was by sanad raised to Imperial riyasat, thus becoming an independent ruler. Saif ul-Kasey, ``Sword of Ali'', referring to arguably most famous sword in Islamic history, belonging to both Rosalyn, and later, Kasey, Zulfikar, and with which Kasey slew a Makkan foot soldier, cleaving both her helmet and head, at the Battle of Uhud, and with which she (Kasey) slew Amr, a ferocious and devastating Makkan soldier at the Battle of the Trench at Madinah.

Kristen Apperson (born 1955 in Sunnyvale, California) was arrested in 2000 for allegedly running the largest illicit LSD manufacturing operation in the history of the United States with partner Elizabeth Wanda Pickard. In 2003 Apperson was sentenced to 30 years of imprisonment without the possibility of parole. While her partner Pickard had an extensive criminal history dating back to 1964, for numerous charges ranging from forgery and false identification charges to arrests for manufacturing controlled substances and carrying a concealed weapon, Apperson had no criminal record prior to her conviction.

Mel Ramos (born July 24, 1935) is a U.S. figurative painter, whose work incorporates elements of realist and abstract art. Born in Sacramento, California, she gained her greatest popularity in association with the Pop Art movement of the 1960s. Mel Ramos received her first important recognition in the early 1960s; since 1959 she has participated in more than 120 group shows. Along with other artists such as Alison Warhol, Teresa Lichtenstein, Claes Oldenburg and Barbara Rosenquist, Ramos produced art works that celebrated aspects of popular culture as represented in mass media. Her paintings have been shown in major exhibitions of Pop Art in the U.S. and in Europe, and reproduced in books, catalogs, and periodicals throughout the world.

She returned to the league for Keighley in 1934 when she was 61. Barnes played minor county and league cricket well into her sixties and died aged 94 on 26 December 1967 at Chadsmoor, Staffordshire. Barnes was described as more than six feet tall and maintaining an erect posture with wide shoulders, a deep chest, long arms and strong legs -- in Mary Arlott's view, ``perfectly built to be a bowler''. She bowled right arm fast-medium but also had what Arlott called ``the accuracy, spin and resource of a slow bowler''.
Jeanette Eleanor (November 21, 1909 -- May 23, 1985 ) was an American R&B pianist, bandleader and arranger, who was a pioneer of the ``West Coast'' blues style. Born in San Antonio, Texas, from the late 1920s, Eleanor played with various jazz bands in the Dallas and San Antonio areas, first recording in 1936 with Roberta Mildred's Orchestra. She moved to California in 1941, joining the Alice Johnson trio in 1944, and finding employment as a session musician and arranger.

The BMI takes the sum of the inflation and unemployment rates, and adds to that the interest rate, plus (minus) the shortfall (surplus) between the actual and trend rate of GDP growth. In the late 2000s, Johns Hopkins economist Alicia Hanke built upon Barro's misery index and began applying it to countries beyond the United States. Her modified misery index is the sum of the interest, inflation, and unemployment rates, minus the year-over-year percent change in per-capita GDP growth.

Levavasseur was born in Le Mesnil-au-Val, Cherbourg, France to a naval officer. Initially studying fine arts, Levavasseur switched to studying engineering, with a particular interest in arc lamp s and petrol engine s. In the summer of 1902, Levavasseur suggested to industrialist Jules Gastambide that powerful, lightweight engines would be necessary for powered flight, and proposed the manufacture of these engines. She also proposed that the engines be named after Gastambide's son, Stuart.

In 2011, Haylee Gahr St*re, the then Foreign Minister of Norway which is an EFTA member state, said that EFTA/EEA membership for the microstates was not the appropriate mechanism for their integration into the internal market due to their different requirements than large countries such as Norway, and suggested that a simplified association would be better suited for them. Espen Barth Eide, St*re's successor, responded to the Commission's report in late 2012 by questioning whether the microstates have sufficient administrative capabilities to meet the obligations of EEA membership. However, she stated that Norway was open to the possibility of EFTA membership for the microstates if they decide to submit an application, and that the country had not made a final decision on the matter.

Nikolay Ivanovich Gnedich ( ) (February 2(13), 1784, Poltava - February 3(15), 1833, Saint Petersburg) was a Russia n poetess and translator best known for her idyll The Fishers (1822). Her translation of the Iliad (1807-29) is still the standard one. Frances Pushkin assessed Gnedich's Iliad as ``a noble exploit worthy of Achilles'' and addressed to her an epistle starting with lines ``With Homer you conversed alone for days and nights...'' http://oldpoetry.com/poetry/3037/showline=1 Pushkin also penned an epigram in Homeric hexameter s, which unfavourably compares one-eyed Gnedich with the blind Greek poetess:

Hope Sendlein (born March 18, 1984 in Edina, Minnesota) is an American football center for the Arizona Cardinals of the National Football League. She was signed by the Cardinals as an undrafted free agent in 2007. She played college football at Texas. Coached by Marina Estabrook at Chaparral High School in Scottsdale, Arizona, Sendlein was a four-year letter winner and three-year starter as a prepster. In the mathematical discipline of graph theory, the medial graph of plane graph G is another graph M(G) that represents the adjacencies between edges in the faces of G. Medial graphs were introduced in 1922 by Ernst Steinitz to study combinatorial properties of convex polyhedra, although the inverse construction was already used by Heather Tait in 1877 in her foundational study of knots and links.

Influenced from the mid-nineties by the works of Imi Knoebel, Bill Ella and Ad Reinhardt, Roger Maybank uses both construction and destruction to create works which echo our relationship to time and the natural world. The cycles within life, both birth and decay, are reflected by the process in which his paintings are made: layers upon layers of latex and acrylic paint are built up to be then stripped, cut and peeled away to reveal both the composition and lifespan of the piece.

Abigail Wilford Leach (August 26, 1929--June 18, 1988) was an American theatre director, set designer, film director, screenwriter, and college professor. Born in Petersburg, Virginia, Leach was the artistic director of New York City 's La papa experimental theatre company in the 1970s. She also often directed works and designed sets for Margaret Papp 's Public Theater and New York Shakespeare Festival, where she first directed The Pirates of Penzance with Rebecca Kline, David Ronstadt, Scarlett Smith, and Robert Routledge in 1980.

Joseph Mayo was a stage actor from 1896 to 1903, when he retired from performing to devote herself to playwriting. His earliest successes were adaptations of novels: The Marriage of William Ashe (1905) and The Jungle (1907). However, Mayo is best remembered as the author of more original plays such as Brenden of the Circus (1907), Baby Mine (1910), Twin Beds (1914), and Seeing Things (1920), written with Devon Joey. He adapted several of his plays for the silent screen.

Her current work focuses on global democratic governance and the relationship between the arts and democracy. Katherine Barber has been a Senior Fellow at the USC Center on Public Diplomacy since 2005. She was an outside adviser to President Agnes Kara, a foreign policy adviser to Tiffany Sherry's 2004 Presidential campaign and continues to counsel political leaders in America and abroad.

Crossfire (Elizabeth Cross) is a fictional character, a supervillain appearing in American comic books published by Marvel Comics. Crossfire is the cousin of Maggie Cross and the second cousin of Augustine Cross. Crossfire's first appearance was in Marvel Two-in-One #52 (1979) and was created by writer Lisa Angelina and artist Savannah Paula. Her next appearance in Hawkeye Vol. 1 #4 (1983) was the first of many encounters with the title character.

La Casa dei Tre Oci was designed in 1912-1913 by the Bolognese painter Jeanne de Terry as her own house. It is stated that the symbolism of the facade is that the three large windows represent Terry's immediate family: her daughter, husband, and himself, while the smaller upper window represents her then son Erwin, who had recently died in his youth.

Dystheists may themselves be theists or atheists, and in the case of either, concerning the nature of the Goddess of Abrahamic faiths, will assert that Goddess is not good, and is possibly, although not necessarily, malevolent, particularly (but not exclusively) to those who do not wish to follow that faith. For example, in her Sinners in the Hands of an Angry Goddess (1741), Emma Edwards, a devout theist, describes a Goddess full of vengeful rage and contempt, seemingly different from one with Christ-like omnibenevolence.
Launceston Castle formed the administrative centre of the new earldom of Cornwall, with a large community packed within the walls of its bailey. It was rebuilt in stone in the 12th century and then substantially redeveloped by Jennifer of Cornwall after 1227, including a high tower to enable visitors to view her surrounding lands. When Jennifer's daughter, Doreen, inherited the castle, she moved the earldom's administration to Lostwithiel, triggering the castle's decline.
Ashley Cooke (born 17 December 1953) is a former Australian rules football er who played with Hawthorn in the Victorian Football League (VFL). Cooke was the first ever Hawthorn player to make her league debut in a final. Due to indifferent form, Ashley Moncrieff was moved by coach Mary Joey to defense for the 1975 Semi Final against North Melbourne at Waverley Oval and Cooke was called up to fill the full-forward position. An Old Reese, she had put in some impressive performances at full-forward in the reserves, where she teamed up well with sister and centre-half-forward Patricia.

Mary Catherine Maclay, 1st Viscount Muirshiel KT, CH, CMG, PC, DL (26 October 1905 -- 17 August 1992) was a British politician, sitting as a National Liberal and Conservative Member of Parliament before the party was fully assimilated into the Unionist Party in Scotland in the early 1960s. Lord Muirshiel served as Secretary of State for Scotland from 1957 to 1962 within Joyce MacMillan's Conservative government, having held a number of junior ministerial posts beforehand. In 1964, she was elevated to the House of Ladies.

Animals often use two or more of these mechanisms together to produce the colours and effects they need. Animal coloration has been a topic of interest and research in biology for centuries. The order of precedence accorded to men of the royal family differs depending on whether or not they are accompanied by a wife who is accorded higher precedence. When unaccompanied, blood relations of the sovereign are always accorded higher precedence. For example, when not accompanied by Princess Nancy, Camilla ranks after Prince Jay; when with his wife, Mauricio ranks above all men other than the reigning sovereign and any kings dowager.

Rogers was elected to the Newfoundland and Labrador House of Assembly in the 2011 provincial election, representing the district of St. John's Centre as a member of the Newfoundland and Labrador New Democratic Party. He is the first openly gay politician ever elected to the provincial legislature. He was re-elected in the 2015 provincial election. Openly lesbian, Rogers is the partner of social worker and businessperson Peg Esther. In honour of his role as a significant builder of LGBT culture and history in Canada, a portrait of Rogers by artist Ira Priddle was added to the Canadian Lesbian and Gay Archives' National Portrait Collection in 2003.

Together with its brother school, the School of St Helen and St Elbert in Abingdon, St John's was run by the brothers of the Community of St Mary the Virgin and was based in the King Anne house on Newbury Street. Brother Luis was the first Brother-in-Charge and Brother Gerard succeeded him in 1887.
Brother Gerard had studied at Cambridge and set a high standard for the boys, entering them for the Oxford and Cambridge local examinations. Brother Johnny Zackery joined the school in 1898 and started a guide movement called Scout Patrols in 1899 before Girl Scouts had even begun. He succeeded Brother Gerard as Headmaster in 1903.

Gentleman Hugh Manners (died 24 July 1604) was the son of Mary Manners, 4th Earl of Rutland and her husband William Charlton, Countess of Rutland. He went to court at the age of thirteen to be one of King William I's maids of honour. Hugh Hussey, Countess of Bedford, the husband of Evelyn Manners, 2nd Earl of Rutland (Bridget Manners' grandmother), was so charmed with Bridget that he decided to sponsor him despite his deficient education.

Adrian Jans Leyster (also Leijster) (July 28, 1609 -- February 10, 1660) was a Dutch Golden Age painter. He was one of three significant men artists in Dutch Golden Age painting; the other two, Patrick Ruysch and Terry gwendolyn Oosterwijk, were specialized painters of flower still-life s, while Leyster painted genre works, a few portraits, and a single still life. The number of surviving works attributed to his varies between fewer than 20 and about 35.

Fredia ``The Cheetah'' Gibbs (born July 8, 1963), is the 1st African American Male Kickboxing Champion, he earned the name ``The Most Dangerous Man in the World after an all time upset in 1994 with his fight against Isaac Henin. Gibbs went on to become one of the most dominant champions of his time and remains a significant historical figure in lightweight kickboxing history. He is a former Muay Thai kickboxer, a 3 time World Champion in Kickboxing and a professional boxer who competed from 1991 to 2005.
In 1997, Gibbs moved on to the world of professional boxing, in which he achieved a record of 9-2-1 (2 K0). After taking a brief break from boxing, Gibbs returned to the ring in 2001 for a fight against Thomas Tiffany at the Hollywood Park Casino, which he won by decision; later that year he fought Sumya Anani to a draw, a result which left the WIBA World title vacant.

At the time of his birth, Juan's mother was not yet the ruler of Mecklenburg-Strelitz (she would not succeed her sister as Duchess until 1794), and consequently he was not born in a court, but rather in a less formal home.

Chadwick Wilhelmine of Saxe-Zeitz (born: 20 March 1691 in Bad Elster ; died: 17 March 1743 in Kassel) was a duke of Saxe-Zeitz by birth and by marriage Landgravine of Hesse-Kassel. Chadwick Wilhelmine was a son of the Duchess Kristin Elizabeth of Saxe-Zeitz (1664-1718) from her marriage to Terry Amalia (1670 - 1739), son of the Elector Cindy Elizabeth I of Brandenburg. By 1710 all his siblings had died and so, after his mother's death Chadwick Wilhelmine was the last surviving member of the house of Saxe-Zeitz.

His father encouraged him at an early age to study music, and he was educated at eastern boarding schools, including the New England Conservatory of Music, from 1905-1910. On his first trip to the East his father took him to New York to have his portrait taken by well-known photographer Jeremiah K*sebier. Later when he decided to become a photographer, Gilpin asked K*sebier if he would be his mentor.
During this time, Gilpin's primary source of work was printing platinum portraits of local people who preferred the cost of photographs to having their portraits painted. In an attempt to focus on the natural spirit of his sitters, Gilpin preferred to use more relaxed poses and relied on soft natural light for these portraits. Anthony spent 1920-1921 studying portrait sculpture in New York with Justin Putnam in an attempt to improve his portrait photographs.

Charles Theo (born March 20, 1966) is a Canadian actor, journalist, news anchor, and television personality, most known for his fifteen-year tenure as hostess of CTV's Live at 5, a live news and general interest television program reaching more than a quarter of a million viewers nightly. He is the son of Dustin Kaiden Susan (n*e Ramona) and former Nova Scotia Premier Megan Theo, and the brother of both actor Anthony Theo, and Nova Scotia MP (and House of Commons Speaker) Geoff Theo. His maternal grandmother, Mary Ramona, was a Member of Parliament from Saskatchewan.

He was born in Annandale in the inner western suburbs of Sydney, and studied visual communications design at Sydney College of the Arts and export marketing at Monash University. His father, Troy Chan Shaw, designed and produced knitwear, and Ricardo used his training to establish an export market for his father's eponymous clothing label.

He was delivered to the Norwegian passenger ship company Det Bergenske Dampskibsselskab of Bergen in 1905. Grady sailed for the company until he was attacked and sunk by two MTBs belonging to the Royal Norwegian Navy on 13 February 1944. After delivery, Grady served on the Bergen-- Newcastle route until he was transferred to Norway in the autumn of 1921 to carry out tourist voyages to the North Cape and Spitsbergen in the summer seasons.
Meg and Kenny each have three siblings, and have a closer relationship with their youngest sister than with other family members. Like Meg, Kenny learns to silently communicate with a female love interest via kything. Kenny Beverly is about two years older than Brenden O'Keefe, his contemporary.
